Playbook four, the network is down.

The symptoms are an inability to reach external sites, sluggish dee-en-ess, or s-s-h connections dropping. This is exactly the layered flow from the networking notebook, applied methodically, where each step assumes the previous one worked.

Layer one: do I even have an interface and an address? Check that no interface is down, and that you actually hold an eye-pee address. Layer two: can I reach my own gateway? Look at the routing table to find the gateway, then ping it; if it does not answer, the problem is local, on your own segment. Layer three: can I reach the wider internet by raw address? Ping a stable public address, which deliberately bypasses dee-en-ess; if the gateway answers but this does not, something between you and the outside world is blocking traffic.

Layer four: does dee-en-ess resolve? Use dig, and then dig again against a public server to bypass your own resolver; if the public query works but your normal one does not, your resolver is the broken piece. Layer five: where does the path die? Trace-route, or the live m-t-r tool, shows which hop along the route fails. Layer six: is the target's port actually reachable? Test it directly with net-cat or curl. And layer seven, on the server side: am I even listening? List the listening sockets with their owning processes, and read the relevant service's recent logs. As a last resort, watch the actual packets with t-c-p-dump to see whether your queries are leaving the machine at all. The common quick fixes are restarting the network manager when there is no address, or pointing at a public resolver when dee-en-ess is the fault.
